[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Warmingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Warmisham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Warmisham","meanings":["English: locative name from Warmingham (Cheshire). The place-name was formerly pronounced ‘Warmincham’ (compare the current spelling of  <i>Altrincham</i>, also in Cheshire, pronounced ‘Altringham’). This could be spelt as  <i>Warmingham</i> with the  <i>-g-</i> prounced as ‘soft’ /dʒ/,  <i>Warmincham</i>, or  <i>Warminsham</i> as illustrated by the surname. In some forms the  <i>-n-</i> in the second syllable was lost, including the variant that appears in Lancs, where the final  <i>-sham</i> has been replaced by the characteristic Lancs place-name element  <i>-shaw</i>. <i>Warmiham</i> and  <i>Warminham</i> seem to be aberrations."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ellen de Warmingham was born in 1133, in Warmingham, Cheshire, England, her father, Warmingham, was 20 and her mother, Warmingham, was 20. She married Roger de Mainwaring about 1154, in Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1180, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 47, and was buried in England."},"et":{"1133–1180":"1133–1180","1130–1195":"1130–1195","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1163–1240":"1163–1240","1163–Female":"1163–Surnud","1166–Male":"1166–Surnud","1168–Male":"1168–Surnud","1157–Male":"1157–Surnud","1168–1210":"1168–1210","1113–Male":"1113–Surnud","1113–Female":"1113–Surnud","1163":"1163","1240":"1240","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","1180":"1180","1168":"1168","1113":"1113","1157":"1157","1133":"1133","Abt 1154":"umbes 1154","1155":"1155","1210":"1210","1166":"1166","about 1168":"umbes 1168","about 1166":"umbes 1166","about 1163":"umbes 1163","Dunham Massey, Cheshire, England":"Dunham Massey, Cheshire, England","England":"England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warmingham, Cheshire, England":"Warmingham, Cheshire, England","Warmingham, Northwich, Cheshire, England":"Warmingham, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1133–1180":"1133–1180","1130–1195":"1130–1195","1155–Male":"1155–Kuollut","1163–1240":"1163–1240","1163–Female":"1163–Kuollut","1166–Male":"1166–Kuollut","1168–Male":"1168–Kuollut","1157–Male":"1157–Kuollut","1168–1210":"1168–1210","1113–Male":"1113–Kuollut","1113–Female":"1113–Kuollut","1163":"1163","1240":"1240","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","1180":"1180","1168":"1168","1113":"1113","1157":"1157","1133":"1133","Abt 1154":"noin